    seasonalMaintenancePara: "Twin Cities landscape maintenance season runs April through October active. Frost-law truck restrictions on MnDOT county roads (typically March-May) limit heavy-material delivery. Spring cleanup includes winter-salt-damaged perennial replacement, lawn aeration, and compost topdressing. Summer irrigation runs June through August. Fall cleanup (September 15-November 15) includes sprinkler blow-out (mandatory before first freeze at $75-$150), leaf collection, and bed winterizing. Winter pruning of deciduous fruit and roses happens March.",
    stormwaterPara: "Minnesota Pollution Control Agency Stormwater Permit Program (MS4 permit) applies to any residential project creating impervious-surface impact above thresholds. Minneapolis Stormwater Management Ordinance requires on-site detention for projects creating over 15,000 sqft of impervious surface. Metropolitan Council coordinates regional standards. Mississippi Watershed Management Organization cost-shares rain gardens and bioretention. Minneapolis and Saint Paul each have Green Stormwater Infrastructure grant programs.",
    commonScamPara: "The dominant Twin Cities landscaping scam is the post-storm door-to-door tree-cleanup crew offering limb removal for $800-$3,500 cash, demanding upfront payment, and disappearing. Minnesota Department of Labor and Industry licenses residential builders but not landscape contractors generally. Verify the MN DOLI residential-builder lookup, $15,000 bond minimum for licensed builders, and $100K general liability insurance. Minnesota AG Consumer Protection tracks repeat complaints. MCNLP and ISA are the baseline credentials for landscape and arborist verification."
